1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,820
Midnight, you count the till. It's 40 francs short.

2
00:00:04,600 --> 00:00:12,900
Not a disaster, but 40 francs. And here's the thing that keeps an owner up at night. You have no idea where it went.

3
00:00:13,980 --> 00:00:14,820
A wrong change.

4
00:00:16,020 --> 00:00:18,340
A missed sale. A hand in the drawer.

5
00:00:19,140 --> 00:00:23,680
The old till just shrugs. One drawer. All day, every hand in it.

6
00:00:24,440 --> 00:00:25,920
The money is a blur.

7
00:00:26,800 --> 00:00:32,120
On a shared till, you can't even ask the right question. Three people were today.

8
00:00:33,060 --> 00:00:39,620
The shortfall has no name, no time, no story. So you do what every shop owner does.

9
00:00:40,480 --> 00:00:45,200
You sigh. You eat the 40 francs, and you hope it's less tomorrow.

10
00:00:46,560 --> 00:00:53,820
Banco does it differently. You start your shift by counting your float, your drawer, your number.

11
00:00:53,820 --> 00:01:00,020
From that second, every sale, every paid in, every paid out is tied to you.

12
00:01:00,480 --> 00:01:06,160
Not the till, you. At the end, you count the cash back. And the till tells you

13
00:01:07,020 --> 00:01:12,800
what it should be to the francs. Expect it. Count it. The difference right there.

14
00:01:13,820 --> 00:01:17,560
Now that 40 francs is in a mystery. It's Maria's drawer.

15
00:01:18,280 --> 00:01:24,320
Tuesday, the evening shift. Maybe it's an honest miscount. Maybe it's a coaching moment.

16
00:01:25,040 --> 00:01:31,320
Either way, you can see it. That's not suspicion. That's just light.

17
00:01:32,220 --> 00:01:37,740
You can't fix what you can't see. Banco doesn't accuse anyone. It just counts.

18
00:01:38,560 --> 00:01:43,880
So you never have to wonder again, a drawer that closes because it tells the truth.
